"section_name": "U.S.", "word_count": "1563", "source": "The New York Times", "subsection_name": null, "lead_paragraph": "A $48 million grant for Isle de Jean Charles, La., is the first allocation of federal tax dollars to move an entire community struggling with the effects of climate change.", "pub_date": "2016-05-03T02:03:26Z", "news_desk": "National", "headline": {"kicker": "Carbon's Casualties", "print_headline": "Resettling the First American \u2018Climate Refugees\u2019", "main": "Resettling the First American \u2018Climate Refugees\u2019", "content_kicker": "Carbon's Casualties"}, "print_page": "1", "snippet": "A $48 million grant for Isle de Jean Charles, La., is the first allocation of federal tax dollars to move an entire community struggling with the effects of climate change.", "_id": "572806f338f0d80b105e4122", "slideshow_credits": null, "abstract": "Isle de Jean Charles, La, is one of first communities to receive federal tax dollars from Dept of Housing and Urban Development to relocate because of climate change, but many residents--mostly members of Biloxi-Chitimacha-Choctaw tribe--are wary of leaving; attachment to eroding island runs deep, and many residents worry about work opportunities elsewhere and whether they will be accepted by their new neighbors (Series: Carbon's Casualties)."}